n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we enhance the adversarial robustness of trajectory prediction models in autonomous vehicles to prevent malicious attacks that manipulate driving behaviors?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Addressing adversarial robustness in trajectory prediction is crucial for ensuring the safety and reliability of autonomous vehicles. Solving this problem will advance the field of autonomous systems by providing methods to detect and mitigate adversarial attacks, which can have significant practical applications in real-world deployments of AVs. This research will also influence future research in developing more secure and resilient AI models.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Enhancing adversarial robustness involves creating sophisticated and realistic adversarial attacks and developing effective defenses. Challenges include ensuring that adversarial examples are natural and indistinguishable from real trajectories, optimizing multiple attack dimensions simultaneously, and designing robust defense mechanisms that can generalize across different scenarios and models. Naive approaches may fail due to the complexity of trajectory dynamics and the need for semantically meaningful attacks and defenses.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has primarily focused on evaluating trajectory prediction models using standard benchmarks without considering security or robustness against adversarial attacks. The unique challenges of trajectory prediction, such as the need for naturalness and the complexity of defining attack objectives, have not been fully addressed. Additionally, there is a lack of comprehensive methodologies for both crafting adversarial attacks and developing robust defenses in this context.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed approach involves using stylized text-to-image generation techniques, such as learnable style tokens and DDIM inversion, to design realistic adversarial attacks and develop defensive mechanisms. The methodology includes refining trajectory prediction prompts using learnable style tokens and employing DDIM inversion to detect adversarial perturbations. We will evaluate the effectiveness of our approach on 10 different combinations of prediction models and trajectory datasets, using metrics such as average lateral/longitudinal deviation and detection accuracy of adversarial examples. Expected outcomes include improved adversarial robustness of trajectory prediction models and a deeper understanding of the vulnerabilities in current AV systems."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': ['In Session 7a61473d-bad2-4f38-bb05-565a85537981 \nFrom agent3 to agent1: Hi agent1, I have started refining the research proposal based on our previous discussions. Here are the refined research questions and methodology. Could you please provide your feedback on these sections?\n'], 'total_milestones': 0, 'agent_kpis': {}}], 'planning_scores': [-1, -1, -1], 'communication_scores': [-1, -1, -1], 'token_usage': 129663, 'agent_kpis': {}, 'total_milestones': 0, 'task_evaluation': {'innovation': 4, 'safety': 5, 'feasibility': 4}}
